#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:5
msgid "Usage and Invocations"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:11
msgid "Calling pytest through ``python -m pytest``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:15
msgid ""
"You can invoke testing through the Python interpreter from the command line::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:17
msgid "python -m pytest [...]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:19
msgid ""
"This is almost equivalent to invoking the command line script ``pytest "
"[...]`` directly, except that calling via ``python`` will also add the "
"current directory to ``sys.path``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:23
msgid "Possible exit codes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:25
msgid "Running ``pytest`` can result in six different exit codes:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:0
msgid "Exit code 0"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:27
msgid "All tests were collected and passed successfully"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:0
msgid "Exit code 1"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:28
msgid "Tests were collected and run but some of the tests failed"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:0
msgid "Exit code 2"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:29
msgid "Test execution was interrupted by the user"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:0
msgid "Exit code 3"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:30
msgid "Internal error happened while executing tests"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:0
msgid "Exit code 4"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:31
msgid "pytest command line usage error"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:0
msgid "Exit code 5"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:32
msgid "No tests were collected"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:35
msgid "Getting help on version, option names, environment variables"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:39
msgid ""
"pytest --version   # shows where pytest was imported from\n"
"pytest --fixtures  # show available builtin function arguments\n"
"pytest -h | --help # show help on command line and config file options"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:47
msgid "Stopping after the first (or N) failures"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:49
msgid "To stop the testing process after the first (N) failures::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:51
msgid ""
"pytest -x            # stop after first failure\n"
"pytest --maxfail=2    # stop after two failures"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:57
msgid "Specifying tests / selecting tests"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:59
msgid ""
"Pytest supports several ways to run and select tests from the command-line."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:61
msgid "**Run tests in a module**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:65
msgid "pytest test_mod.py"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:67
msgid "**Run tests in a directory**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:71
msgid "pytest testing/"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:73
msgid "**Run tests by keyword expressions**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:77
msgid "pytest -k \"MyClass and not method\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:79
msgid ""
"This will run tests which contain names that match the given *string "
"expression*, which can include Python operators that use filenames, class "
"names and function names as variables. The example above will run "
"``TestMyClass.test_something``  but not ``TestMyClass.test_method_simple``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:85
msgid "**Run tests by node ids**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:87
msgid ""
"Each collected test is assigned a unique ``nodeid`` which consist of the "
"module filename followed by specifiers like class names, function names and "
"parameters from parametrization, separated by ``::`` characters."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:90
msgid "To run a specific test within a module::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:92
msgid "pytest test_mod.py::test_func"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:95
msgid "Another example specifying a test method in the command line::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:97
msgid "pytest test_mod.py::TestClass::test_method"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:99
msgid "**Run tests by marker expressions**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:103
msgid "pytest -m slow"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:105
msgid ""
"Will run all tests which are decorated with the ``@pytest.mark.slow`` "
"decorator."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:107
msgid "For more information see :ref:`marks <mark>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:109
msgid "**Run tests from packages**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:113
msgid "pytest --pyargs pkg.testing"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:115
msgid ""
"This will import ``pkg.testing`` and use its filesystem location to find and "
"run tests from."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:119
msgid "Modifying Python traceback printing"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:121
msgid "Examples for modifying traceback printing::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:123
msgid ""
"pytest --showlocals # show local variables in tracebacks\n"
"pytest -l           # show local variables (shortcut)\n"
"\n"
"pytest --tb=auto    # (default) 'long' tracebacks for the first and last\n"
"                     # entry, but 'short' style for the other entries\n"
"pytest --tb=long    # exhaustive, informative traceback formatting\n"
"pytest --tb=short   # shorter traceback format\n"
"pytest --tb=line    # only one line per failure\n"
"pytest --tb=native  # Python standard library formatting\n"
"pytest --tb=no      # no traceback at all"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:134
msgid ""
"The ``--full-trace`` causes very long traces to be printed on error (longer "
"than ``--tb=long``). It also ensures that a stack trace is printed on "
"**KeyboardInterrupt** (Ctrl+C). This is very useful if the tests are taking "
"too long and you interrupt them with Ctrl+C to find out where the tests are "
"*hanging*. By default no output will be shown (because KeyboardInterrupt is "
"caught by pytest). By using this option you make sure a trace is shown."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:146
msgid "Detailed summary report"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:150
msgid ""
"The ``-r`` flag can be used to display test results summary at the end of "
"the test session, making it easy in large test suites to get a clear picture "
"of all failures, skips, xfails, etc."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:153
msgid "Example::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:155
msgid ""
"$ pytest -ra\n"
"=========================== test session starts "
"============================\n"
"platform linux -- Python 3.x.y, pytest-3.x.y, py-1.x.y, pluggy-0.x.y\n"
"rootdir: $REGENDOC_TMPDIR, inifile:\n"
"collected 0 items\n"
"\n"
"======================= no tests ran in 0.12 seconds ======================="
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:163
msgid ""
"The ``-r`` options accepts a number of characters after it, with ``a`` used "
"above meaning \"all except passes\"."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:165
msgid "Here is the full list of available characters that can be used:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:167
msgid "``f`` - failed"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:168
msgid "``E`` - error"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:169
msgid "``s`` - skipped"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:170
msgid "``x`` - xfailed"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:171
msgid "``X`` - xpassed"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:172
msgid "``p`` - passed"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:173
msgid "``P`` - passed with output"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:174
msgid "``a`` - all except ``pP``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:176
msgid ""
"More than one character can be used, so for example to only see failed and "
"skipped tests, you can execute::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:178
msgid ""
"$ pytest -rfs\n"
"=========================== test session starts "
"============================\n"
"platform linux -- Python 3.x.y, pytest-3.x.y, py-1.x.y, pluggy-0.x.y\n"
"rootdir: $REGENDOC_TMPDIR, inifile:\n"
"collected 0 items\n"
"\n"
"======================= no tests ran in 0.12 seconds ======================="
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:189
msgid "Dropping to PDB_ (Python Debugger) on failures"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:193
msgid ""
"Python comes with a builtin Python debugger called PDB_.  ``pytest`` allows "
"one to drop into the PDB_ prompt via a command line option::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:196
msgid "pytest --pdb"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:198
msgid ""
"This will invoke the Python debugger on every failure (or "
"KeyboardInterrupt). Often you might only want to do this for the first "
"failing test to understand a certain failure situation::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:202
msgid ""
"pytest -x --pdb   # drop to PDB on first failure, then end test session\n"
"pytest --pdb --maxfail=3  # drop to PDB for first three failures"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:205
msgid ""
"Note that on any failure the exception information is stored on ``sys."
"last_value``, ``sys.last_type`` and ``sys.last_traceback``. In interactive "
"use, this allows one to drop into postmortem debugging with any debug tool. "
"One can also manually access the exception information, for example::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:211
msgid ""
">>> import sys\n"
">>> sys.last_traceback.tb_lineno\n"
"42\n"
">>> sys.last_value\n"
"AssertionError('assert result == \"ok\"',)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:220
msgid "Dropping to PDB_ (Python Debugger) at the start of a test"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:223
msgid ""
"``pytest`` allows one to drop into the PDB_ prompt immediately at the start "
"of each test via a command line option::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:225
msgid "pytest --trace"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:227
msgid "This will invoke the Python debugger at the start of every test."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:232
msgid "Setting breakpoints"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:236
msgid ""
"To set a breakpoint in your code use the native Python ``import pdb;pdb."
"set_trace()`` call in your code and pytest automatically disables its output "
"capture for that test:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:239
msgid "Output capture in other tests is not affected."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:240
msgid ""
"Any prior test output that has already been captured and will be processed "
"as such."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:242
msgid ""
"Any later output produced within the same test will not be captured and will "
"instead get sent directly to ``sys.stdout``. Note that this holds true even "
"for test output occurring after you exit the interactive PDB_ tracing "
"session and continue with the regular test run."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:251
msgid "Using the builtin breakpoint function"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:253
msgid ""
"Python 3.7 introduces a builtin ``breakpoint()`` function. Pytest supports "
"the use of ``breakpoint()`` with the following behaviours:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:256
msgid ""
"When ``breakpoint()`` is called and ``PYTHONBREAKPOINT`` is set to the "
"default value, pytest will use the custom internal PDB trace UI instead of "
"the system default ``Pdb``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:257
msgid ""
"When tests are complete, the system will default back to the system ``Pdb`` "
"trace UI."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:258
msgid ""
"With ``--pdb`` passed to pytest, the custom internal Pdb trace UI is used "
"with both ``breakpoint()`` and failed tests/unhandled exceptions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:259
msgid "``--pdbcls`` can be used to specify a custom debugger class."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:264
msgid "Profiling test execution duration"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:268
msgid "To get a list of the slowest 10 test durations::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:270
msgid "pytest --durations=10"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:272
msgid ""
"By default, pytest will not show test durations that are too small (<0.01s) "
"unless ``-vv`` is passed on the command-line."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:275
msgid "Creating JUnitXML format files"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:277
msgid ""
"To create result files which can be read by Jenkins_ or other Continuous "
"integration servers, use this invocation::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:280
msgid "pytest --junitxml=path"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:282
msgid "to create an XML file at ``path``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:286
msgid ""
"To set the name of the root test suite xml item, you can configure the "
"``junit_suite_name`` option in your config file:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:288
msgid ""
"[pytest]\n"
"junit_suite_name = my_suite"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:296
msgid "record_property"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:301
msgid ""
"Fixture renamed from ``record_xml_property`` to ``record_property`` as user "
"properties are now available to all reporters. ``record_xml_property`` is "
"now deprecated."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:305
msgid ""
"If you want to log additional information for a test, you can use the "
"``record_property`` fixture:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:308
msgid ""
"def test_function(record_property):\n"
"    record_property(\"example_key\", 1)\n"
"    assert True"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:314
msgid ""
"This will add an extra property ``example_key=\"1\"`` to the generated "
"``testcase`` tag:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:317
msgid ""
"<testcase classname=\"test_function\" file=\"test_function.py\" line=\"0\" "
"name=\"test_function\" time=\"0.0009\">\n"
"  <properties>\n"
"    <property name=\"example_key\" value=\"1\" />\n"
"  </properties>\n"
"</testcase>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:325
msgid ""
"Alternatively, you can integrate this functionality with custom markers:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:327
msgid ""
"# content of conftest.py\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"def pytest_collection_modifyitems(session, config, items):\n"
"    for item in items:\n"
"        for marker in item.iter_markers(name=\"test_id\"):\n"
"            test_id = marker.args[0]\n"
"            item.user_properties.append((\"test_id\", test_id))"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:338
msgid "And in your tests:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:340
msgid ""
"# content of test_function.py\n"
"import pytest\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.mark.test_id(1501)\n"
"def test_function():\n"
"    assert True"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:350
msgid "Will result in:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:352
msgid ""
"<testcase classname=\"test_function\" file=\"test_function.py\" line=\"0\" "
"name=\"test_function\" time=\"0.0009\">\n"
"  <properties>\n"
"    <property name=\"test_id\" value=\"1501\" />\n"
"  </properties>\n"
"</testcase>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:362
msgid ""
"``record_property`` is an experimental feature and may change in the future."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:364
msgid ""
"Also please note that using this feature will break any schema verification. "
"This might be a problem when used with some CI servers."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:368
msgid "record_xml_attribute"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:372
msgid ""
"To add an additional xml attribute to a testcase element, you can use "
"``record_xml_attribute`` fixture. This can also be used to override existing "
"values:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:375
msgid ""
"def test_function(record_xml_attribute):\n"
"    record_xml_attribute(\"assertions\", \"REQ-1234\")\n"
"    record_xml_attribute(\"classname\", \"custom_classname\")\n"
"    print(\"hello world\")\n"
"    assert True"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:383
msgid ""
"Unlike ``record_property``, this will not add a new child element. Instead, "
"this will add an attribute ``assertions=\"REQ-1234\"`` inside the generated "
"``testcase`` tag and override the default ``classname`` with "
"``\"classname=custom_classname\"``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:387
msgid ""
"<testcase classname=\"custom_classname\" file=\"test_function.py\" "
"line=\"0\" name=\"test_function\" time=\"0.003\" assertions=\"REQ-1234\">\n"
"    <system-out>\n"
"        hello world\n"
"    </system-out>\n"
"</testcase>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:397
msgid ""
"``record_xml_attribute`` is an experimental feature, and its interface might "
"be replaced by something more powerful and general in future versions. The "
"functionality per-se will be kept, however."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:401
msgid ""
"Using this over ``record_xml_property`` can help when using ci tools to "
"parse the xml report. However, some parsers are quite strict about the "
"elements and attributes that are allowed. Many tools use an xsd schema (like "
"the example below) to validate incoming xml. Make sure you are using "
"attribute names that are allowed by your parser."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:406
msgid "Below is the Scheme used by Jenkins to validate the XML report:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:408
msgid ""
"<xs:element name=\"testcase\">\n"
"    <xs:complexType>\n"
"        <xs:sequence>\n"
"            <xs:element ref=\"skipped\" minOccurs=\"0\" maxOccurs=\"1\"/>\n"
"            <xs:element ref=\"error\" minOccurs=\"0\" "
"maxOccurs=\"unbounded\"/>\n"
"            <xs:element ref=\"failure\" minOccurs=\"0\" "
"maxOccurs=\"unbounded\"/>\n"
"            <xs:element ref=\"system-out\" minOccurs=\"0\" "
"maxOccurs=\"unbounded\"/>\n"
"            <xs:element ref=\"system-err\" minOccurs=\"0\" "
"maxOccurs=\"unbounded\"/>\n"
"        </xs:sequence>\n"
"        <xs:attribute name=\"name\" type=\"xs:string\" use=\"required\"/>\n"
"        <xs:attribute name=\"assertions\" type=\"xs:string\" "
"use=\"optional\"/>\n"
"        <xs:attribute name=\"time\" type=\"xs:string\" use=\"optional\"/>\n"
"        <xs:attribute name=\"classname\" type=\"xs:string\" use=\"optional\"/"
">\n"
"        <xs:attribute name=\"status\" type=\"xs:string\" use=\"optional\"/>\n"
"    </xs:complexType>\n"
"</xs:element>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:428
msgid "LogXML: add_global_property"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:432
msgid ""
"If you want to add a properties node in the testsuite level, which may "
"contains properties that are relevant to all testcases you can use ``LogXML."
"add_global_properties``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:435
msgid ""
"import pytest\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.fixture(scope=\"session\")\n"
"def log_global_env_facts(f):\n"
"\n"
"    if pytest.config.pluginmanager.hasplugin(\"junitxml\"):\n"
"        my_junit = getattr(pytest.config, \"_xml\", None)\n"
"\n"
"    my_junit.add_global_property(\"ARCH\", \"PPC\")\n"
"    my_junit.add_global_property(\"STORAGE_TYPE\", \"CEPH\")\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.mark.usefixtures(log_global_env_facts.__name__)\n"
"def start_and_prepare_env():\n"
"    pass\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"class TestMe(object):\n"
"    def test_foo(self):\n"
"        assert True"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:459
msgid ""
"This will add a property node below the testsuite node to the generated xml:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:461
msgid ""
"<testsuite errors=\"0\" failures=\"0\" name=\"pytest\" skips=\"0\" "
"tests=\"1\" time=\"0.006\">\n"
"  <properties>\n"
"    <property name=\"ARCH\" value=\"PPC\"/>\n"
"    <property name=\"STORAGE_TYPE\" value=\"CEPH\"/>\n"
"  </properties>\n"
"  <testcase classname=\"test_me.TestMe\" file=\"test_me.py\" line=\"16\" "
"name=\"test_foo\" time=\"0.000243663787842\"/>\n"
"</testsuite>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:473
msgid ""
"This is an experimental feature, and its interface might be replaced by "
"something more powerful and general in future versions. The functionality "
"per-se will be kept."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:478
msgid "Creating resultlog format files"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:482
msgid "This option is rarely used and is scheduled for removal in 4.0."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:484
msgid ""
"An alternative for users which still need similar functionality is to use "
"the `pytest-tap <https://pypi.org/project/pytest-tap/>`_ plugin which "
"provides a stream of test data."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:488
msgid ""
"If you have any concerns, please don't hesitate to `open an issue <https://"
"github.com/pytest-dev/pytest/issues>`_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:491
msgid "To create plain-text machine-readable result files you can issue::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:493
msgid "pytest --resultlog=path"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:495
msgid ""
"and look at the content at the ``path`` location.  Such files are used e.g. "
"by the `PyPy-test`_ web page to show test results over several revisions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:502
msgid "Sending test report to online pastebin service"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:504
msgid "**Creating a URL for each test failure**::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:506
msgid "pytest --pastebin=failed"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:508
msgid ""
"This will submit test run information to a remote Paste service and provide "
"a URL for each failure.  You may select tests as usual or add for example ``-"
"x`` if you only want to send one particular failure."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:512
msgid "**Creating a URL for a whole test session log**::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:514
msgid "pytest --pastebin=all"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:516
msgid "Currently only pasting to the http://bpaste.net service is implemented."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:519
msgid "Disabling plugins"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:521
msgid ""
"To disable loading specific plugins at invocation time, use the ``-p`` "
"option together with the prefix ``no:``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:524
msgid ""
"Example: to disable loading the plugin ``doctest``, which is responsible for "
"executing doctest tests from text files, invoke pytest like this::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:527
msgid "pytest -p no:doctest"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:532
msgid "Calling pytest from Python code"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:536
msgid "You can invoke ``pytest`` from Python code directly::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:538
msgid "pytest.main()"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:540
msgid ""
"this acts as if you would call \"pytest\" from the command line. It will not "
"raise ``SystemExit`` but return the exitcode instead. You can pass in "
"options and arguments::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:544
msgid "pytest.main(['-x', 'mytestdir'])"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:546
msgid "You can specify additional plugins to ``pytest.main``::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:548
msgid ""
"# content of myinvoke.py\n"
"import pytest\n"
"class MyPlugin(object):\n"
"    def pytest_sessionfinish(self):\n"
"        print(\"*** test run reporting finishing\")\n"
"\n"
"pytest.main([\"-qq\"], plugins=[MyPlugin()])"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:556
msgid ""
"Running it will show that ``MyPlugin`` was added and its hook was invoked::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:559
msgid ""
"$ python myinvoke.py\n"
".                                                                    "
"[100%]*** test run reporting finishing"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:565
msgid ""
"Calling ``pytest.main()`` will result in importing your tests and any "
"modules that they import. Due to the caching mechanism of python's import "
"system, making subsequent calls to ``pytest.main()`` from the same process "
"will not reflect changes to those files between the calls. For this reason, "
"making multiple calls to ``pytest.main()`` from the same process (in order "
"to re-run tests, for example) is not recommended."
msgstr ""
